<subSubSection id="8F41348ABCB13A0159FFAE9EB86A2C67" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="2C93318EA49A9A7D097354AF6366A2EE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0D4401ED7A1C5FA34B9CCD9581AF66B2" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This species can be recognised by its distinctive subhypocrateriform corolla, the tube only expanding just below the limb. Yatskievich and Mason (1984) and McDonald (1995) recognised two varieties but these overlap morphologically and geographically. The type has a pale pink or white corolla mostly 5-10 cm long with the inner sepals 11-14 mm in length. 
<taxonomicName id="19C1B1A584940CD153CB4C20210602B8" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="tenuiloba" variety="lemmonii">
<emphasis id="099BA4B2414A881FC31D38BCFCB7D73F" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Var. 
<emphasis id="E968A2DDA0CDD217288E61CE0C4D6AF2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">lemmonii</emphasis>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more western in its distribution and has a darker, smaller corolla 3.3-5.2 cm long with shorter inner sepals &lt;10 mm long.
</paragraph>
